caption: Table 2: Credit Card Fraud Detection Experiment
description: This table presents the results of a real-data experiment on credit card fraud detection using the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure. It shows the average false detection proportion (FDP) before and after applying the INCREASE-c algorithm with different values of c (corruption budget).  The table also displays the average number of alleged frauds before and after the adversarial attack.  The results illustrate how INCREASE-c can increase the FDR (false discovery rate) beyond the control level.
section: 5.2 Real-Data Experiment: Credit Card Fraud Detection

caption: Table 3: Sample Average (104-batch) estimates of EzFDP[BHq;z'] under MOVE-1 and INCREASE-1 (in parentheses) when μ₁ = 0,1,2 and N = 103, q = 0.10, πο = 0.90, and all σ² = 1.
description: This table compares the average performance of the optimal algorithm MOVE-1 and the INCREASE-1 algorithm.  It shows the average estimated false discovery proportion (FDP) under both algorithms,  across 104 simulation batches, for three different values of μ₁ (1, 2, and 0).  The table also reports the average distance between the original z-scores and the perturbed z-scores under each algorithm.  It demonstrates that INCREASE-1 achieves nearly identical performance to MOVE-1 in terms of FDP adjustment; however, the perturbation distance is larger for INCREASE-1 on average.
